passages.text: Consumer | Global Retailing, Softlines & Luxury Brands
Read- Through Round- Up: Our Look at Important Data Points for the Softlines Stocks from the Week: Several updates from Softlines brands and retailers this week.

JD Sports (Not Covered): While Europe and UK comps, - \(1.1\%\) and \(- 6.1\%\) , were impacted by the Euro 2024 tournament, North America trends (- 2.3% v. 1Q: - 5.5%), have notably improved due to good performance on new footwear launches, partially offset by key footwear products being at the end of their cycle. Despite the tough macro environment, the company expects FY26 PBTAI to be in- line with market expectations resulting in the stock trading \(+3.3\%\) on the print.

2. Abercrombie (Not Covered): 2Q results delivered a modest beat with revenues inline at \(\) 1.2\(Bm, net income\) \ \(141.4m\) (Street: \(\) 113.0m),\(and EPS\) \ \(2.32\) (Street: \(\) 2.30\(). Management raised FY guidance for net sales, operating margin, and EPS. The stock traded flat on a modest beat.

3. ANTA (Not Covered): 1H revenues increased \(14.3\%\) YOY with increases in all segments: ANTA \(+5.4\%\) FILA \(+8.6\%\) and all other brands \(+61.1\%\) . EPS declined \(7.5\%\) YOY to \(\) 2.48\(. The stock traded down -2\%\) on the print.

4. Bath and Body Works (Not Covered): 2Q revenues and EPS missed Street estimates, with traffic softer than 1Q, Direct Net Sales down -10% YOY, International Sales down -3%, and SG&A delevering 110bps, which altogether lowered operating income to -6% YOY. The company defined a FY tariff impact of \(\) 85m\(with\) \ \(40m\) impacting 3Q and lowered the midpoint of revenue guidance by 10bps to \(+2.0\%\) . The stock was down -8% on the print.

5. Urban Outfitters (Not Covered): 2Q retail comps accelerated to \(+5.6\%\) (from \(+4.8\%\) in 1Q) driving both a YOY acceleration of total retail sales growth that outpaced Street estimates by \(1.9\%\) and a EPS beat of \(\) 0.10\((reported\) \ \(1.58\) , Street \(\) 1.48\$ ). Despite the beat, URBn stock was down - \(6.2\%\) on a moderated wholesale outlook of MSD for 2H which is a steep slowdown from the \(+18\%\) YOY increase in 2Q. The company has worsened its tariff expectations (- 75bp v. prev. guide of - 25bp) and cited the difficulty of comping strong DD.

Our channel work this week touched on sectors across footwear from lifestyle to city specialty.

Recent Trends: Back to School trends remained strong across categories (though border stores have seen some pressure). While Athletic Specialty stores have still been pressured, Value footwear channels have been strong—particularly in Athletic (Nike) and Sandals (BIRK). The focus is quickly shifting to "What happens the 2- 3 weeks after BTS ends?" as consumers continue to show responsiveness to event- driven spending.

Athletic is the strongest category in Value/Family channels (led by Nike). That said, there is still a struggle in Athletic Specialty/City channels as retailers use BTS traffic to continue to clear Dunks (likely to be cleared by holiday).

Vomero 18 is a hit...but watch the Retros: Vomero 18 has been an unmitigated success as a modern update on a popular Nike performance franchise. But the retro style Vomero 5 has started to see quiet buzz emerging online. With several hoped- for trends failing to gain steam (Skate, Low Profile), retailers are looking for another push from the Retro Running category. While Asics and New Balance are leading the charge, Nike has the biggest Retro Running catalogue by far, and it looks to be testing the waters with the retro Vomero 5.

Channel work remains positive on Air Max: We think retailers have big plans for Air Max as they look out to Spring 2026. VaporMax Plus and 95s are seeing solid demand (offsetting softness in 90/270). Basketball momentum is picking up with recent Kobe and Ja Morant products. Quick Note on Jordan Launches: We've been highlighting that Jordan launches have shown significantly improved KPIs for months now. While
that broadly remains the case, we're hearing softness in Retro AJ1 launches even though that franchise is close to clean on inventory. Non- AJ1 retro launches continue to show strong improvement.

Adidas Going on Defense? Our checks continue to pick up softening sell- through, with retailers increasing promotions lately to keep inventory turns up—increasing risks for order cancellations in the back half. Our checks suggest Adidas has started to pivot from being a supportive partner in helping retailers cancel inventories gone to now requiring 1:1 rebooking of orders (i.e. forcing retailers to swap cancellations with another product as opposed to an outright cancel).

Timberland Set for a Strong Winter: Retailers have big order growth after leaving demand on the table last year (with demand still strong well into the spring). VFC is supporting demand in a healthy way, reverting to scarce product allocations to avoid overloading the market.

BIRK Accelerating? Demand for BIRK has grown over the last few months even amid July price increases. The brand has been a clear winner across channels for BTS, and retailers are re- ordering fast after losing out on sales post- BTS last year. Interestingly, closed- toe products aren't working well in every channel. Unlike the Adidas comments above, BIRK is viewed as the best inventory manager in the space, and is quickly and proactively telling retailers to cancel orders early on any signs that turns are slowing—good reinforcement of our long- term thesis for the brand.

Two Key Softlines Brands Winning in Value Channel: Athletic and Sandals are materially outpacing the broader value channel, specifically Nike and BIRK. As we said above, we think BIRK has been accelerating within that channel month- over- month for \(\sim 3\) months now.

SKX Working Well: After abruptly announcing massive tariff driven price increases this spring, Skechers has now dialed back those planned price increases. The brand lost some share in the value channel that it can't get back this year, but retailers are confident it can make up ground again in 2026.
UGG Coming to Value Channel? UGG is not present in the value channel today, but we wouldn't be surprised if the brand tests product in the US value channel in 2H26.

Evercore ISI's recommendations are based on a stock's total forecasted return over the next 12 months. Total forecasted return is equal to the expected percentage price return plus gross dividend yield. We divide our stocks under coverage into three primary ratings categories, with the following return guidelines:
Outperform- the total forecasted return is expected to be greater than the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector.
In Line- the total forecasted return is expected to be in line with the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector.
Underperform- the total forecasted return is expected to be less than the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector.

Coverage Suspended- the rating and target price have been removed pursuant to Evercore ISI policy when Evercore is acting in an advisory capacity in a merger or strategic transaction involving this company and in certain other circumstances.

Rating Suspended- Evercore ISI has suspended the rating and target price for this stock because there is not sufficient fundamental basis for determining, or there are legal, regulatory or policy constraints around publishing, a rating or target price. The previous rating and target price, if any, are no longer in effect for this company and should not be relied upon.
Prior to October 10, 2015, the "Coverage Suspended" and "Rating Suspended" categories were included in the category "Suspended."

FINRA requires that members who use a ratings system with terms other than "Buy," "Hold/Neutral" and "Sell" to equate their own ratings to these categories. For this purpose, and in the Evercore ISI ratings distribution below, our Outperform, In Line, and Underperform ratings can be equated to Buy, Hold and Sell, respectively.
